K-means clustering

tmp <- c(rnorm(30,-3), rnorm(30,3))
x <- cbind(x=tmp, y=rev(tmp))
plot(x)

km <- kmeans(x, centers =2, nstart = 20) 
km

Q. How many points are in each cluster? Q. What component of your result object details - cluster size? size??? size - cluster assignment/membership? cluster - cluster center? center Plot x colored by the kmeans cluster assignment and add cluster centers as blue points

km$centers

plot(x, col = km$cluster)
points(km$centers, col = "blue", pch = 15, cex=3)

First we need to calculate point (dis)similarity

as the Euclidean distance between observations

dist_matrix <- dist(x) # The hclust() function returns a hierarchical have to calculate the dist_matrix befire cakkubf hclust # clustering model hc <- hclust(d = dist_matrix) # the print method is not so useful here hc Call: hclust(d = dist_matrix) Cluster method : complete Distance : euclidean

d <- dist(x)
hc <- hclust(x)
Error in if (is.na(n) || n > 65536L) stop("size cannot be NA nor exceed 65536") : 
  missing value where TRUE/FALSE needed
hc <- hclust(dist(x))
plot(hc)

# Draws a dendrogram
plot(hc)
abline(h=6, col="red", lty=2)
abline(h=4, col="blue")

grp4 <- cutree(hc, h=4 ) 
# Cut into k grps
table(grp4)
grp4
 1  2  3  4 
11 19 19 11 
# Step 1. Generate some example data for clustering
x <- rbind(
 matrix(rnorm(100, mean=0, sd = 0.3), ncol = 2), # c1
 matrix(rnorm(100, mean = 1, sd = 0.3), ncol = 2), # c2
 matrix(c(rnorm(50, mean = 1, sd = 0.3), # c3
 rnorm(50, mean = 0, sd = 0.3)), ncol = 2))
colnames(x) <- c("x", "y")
# Step 2. Plot the data without clustering
plot(x)

# Step 3. Generate colors for known clusters
# (just so we can compare to hclust results)
col <- as.factor( rep(c("c1","c2","c3"), each=50) )
plot(x, col=col)

Q. Use the dist(), hclust(), plot() and cutree() functions to return 2 and 3 clusters Q. How does this compare to your known col groups?

hc <- hclust(dist(x))
plot(hc)
abline(h=1.7, col="sky blue")

to get cluster memebrship vector use cutree() and then use table() to tabulate up how many members in each cluster we have

grps <- cutree(hc, k=3)
table(grps)
grps
 1  2  3 
48 52 50 
plot(x, col=grps)
